<!-- ===== ABSTRACT ===== -->
<div class="page-break">
  <h1>ABSTRACT</h1>
  <br/>
  <p>In the current academic environment, study materials are scattered across multiple informal channels such as WhatsApp groups, personal drives, and email threads, making access inefficient and inequitable. <strong>Study Share</strong> is a full-stack web platform designed to address this critical gap by providing a centralized, AI-powered repository for academic resources accessible to students and faculty.</p>
  <br/>
  <p>The platform enables authenticated users to upload, organize, and browse study materials — including PDFs, notes, and examination papers — categorized by branch, semester, subject, and year. A key distinguishing feature is the integration of Artificial Intelligence through Google's Gemini API for context-aware document Q&amp;A, enabling students to interactively query their study materials rather than passively reading them.</p>
  <br/>
  <p>The system implements a multi-stage background processing pipeline using BullMQ and Redis, which performs OCR (via NVIDIA's PaddleOCR API), generates vector embeddings stored in Pinecone, and structures content for intelligent retrieval. File storage is managed via Cloudinary, with MongoDB Atlas serving as the primary database and Firebase handling authentication and user profiles.</p>
  <br/>
  <p>The frontend is built with Next.js 16 and React 19, featuring a responsive mobile-first design with Tailwind CSS. Role-based access control distinguishes between students, teachers, and administrators, each with dedicated dashboards and capabilities. Additional features include a Monaco-based code editor with sandboxed execution via Judge0, bookmarking, download tracking, and a general-purpose AI chatbot.</p>
  <br/>
  <p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Academic Resource Management, AI-Powered Q&amp;A, Next.js, MongoDB, Firebase, Google Gemini, Vector Embeddings, OCR, BullMQ, Role-Based Access Control.</p>
</div>

