<!-- ===== CHAPTER 1: INTRODUCTION ===== -->
<div class="page-break">
  <h1>CHAPTER 1<br/>INTRODUCTION</h1>

  <h2>1.1 Background</h2>
  <p>The digital transformation of education has accelerated significantly in recent years, driven by the widespread adoption of internet technologies, mobile devices, and cloud computing. However, despite the availability of digital tools, the management and sharing of academic study materials in most Indian engineering colleges remains largely ad hoc. Students rely heavily on informal communication channels such as WhatsApp groups, personal Google Drive links, and Telegram channels to share notes, question papers, and reference materials. These channels, while convenient, suffer from inherent limitations: lack of searchability, poor organization, absence of version control, and no guarantee of content accuracy or relevance.</p>
  <br/>
  <p>Knowledge continuity across academic batches is a persistent challenge. When senior students graduate, valuable notes and solved papers are lost or become inaccessible to junior batches. Faculty members have no standardized mechanism to distribute supplementary materials beyond Learning Management Systems (LMS) that are often underutilized or restricted. Furthermore, the emergence of Artificial Intelligence and Large Language Models (LLMs) presents an unprecedented opportunity to move beyond passive content consumption toward interactive, query-driven learning.</p>
  <br/>
  <p>Study Share was conceived to address these structural gaps. It provides a centralized, role-aware web platform where students and teachers can upload, organize, discover, and interact with academic materials through both conventional browsing and AI-powered conversational interfaces.</p>

  <h2>1.2 Problem Statement</h2>
  <p>The current ecosystem for academic material sharing in engineering colleges is characterized by the following critical problems:</p>
  <br/>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Fragmentation of Resources:</strong> Study materials are distributed across WhatsApp, personal drives, email attachments, and physical photocopies, with no single authoritative repository.</li>
    <li><strong>Lack of Discoverability:</strong> There is no structured search mechanism; students must rely on social networks to locate relevant materials, which is time-consuming and unreliable.</li>
    <li><strong>Knowledge Erosion:</strong> Each graduating batch takes its accumulated study resources with it, depriving junior students of valuable institutional knowledge.</li>
    <li><strong>Passive Consumption:</strong> Even when digital PDFs are available, students must read through lengthy documents manually with no mechanism to ask questions or extract targeted information.</li>
    <li><strong>Absence of Access Control:</strong> Informal sharing channels have no role differentiation — anyone can share anything, with no quality control or verification mechanism.</li>
    <li><strong>No Analytics:</strong> Faculty and administrators have no visibility into which materials are most accessed, what gaps exist in the repository, or how students are using shared resources.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>1.3 Project Objectives</h2>
  <p>The primary objectives of the Study Share platform are as follows:</p>
  <br/>
  <ol>
    <li>To develop a centralized, web-based repository for academic study materials organized by branch, semester, subject, and year.</li>
    <li>To implement a secure, role-based authentication system differentiating students, teachers, and administrators using Firebase Authentication and Google Sign-In.</li>
    <li>To integrate an AI-powered Q&amp;A system using Google Gemini API that enables students to interactively query uploaded documents in natural language.</li>
    <li>To build a scalable background processing pipeline using BullMQ and Redis for asynchronous OCR, text extraction, and vector embedding generation.</li>
    <li>To enable semantic search capabilities using Pinecone vector database, allowing students to find relevant materials beyond simple keyword matching.</li>
    <li>To provide a built-in code execution environment using Monaco Editor and Judge0 API for programming-related academic content.</li>
    <li>To deliver a fully responsive, mobile-first user interface accessible across devices without degradation of functionality.</li>
    <li>To implement an admin dashboard for platform governance, teacher verification, and content moderation.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>1.4 Scope and Limitations</h2>
  <h3>1.4.1 Scope</h3>
  <p>The scope of the Study Share platform encompasses:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Web-based platform accessible on all modern browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge) on desktop and mobile devices.</li>
    <li>Support for engineering college academic materials: PDFs, notes, question papers, presentations.</li>
    <li>Three-role user system: Student, Teacher, and Admin.</li>
    <li>AI-powered document interaction for all uploaded PDF materials that complete OCR processing.</li>
    <li>Semantic vector search across indexed materials.</li>
    <li>Bookmark, download tracking, and material management features.</li>
    <li>Integrated code sandbox supporting Python, JavaScript, Java, C, C++, and other languages via Judge0.</li>
    <li>Admin tools for user management, teacher verification, and content moderation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>1.4.2 Limitations</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>AI Accuracy:</strong> Responses from the Gemini API are probabilistic and may not always be factually accurate; the platform includes a disclaimer to this effect.</li>
    <li><strong>OCR Quality:</strong> The accuracy of text extraction depends on the scan quality of uploaded PDFs; hand-written notes or poor-quality scans may not process correctly.</li>
    <li><strong>Language Support:</strong> The platform currently supports English-language materials only; regional language PDFs may not process accurately.</li>
    <li><strong>Offline Access:</strong> The platform requires an active internet connection; no offline functionality is provided.</li>
    <li><strong>File Types:</strong> Currently limited to PDF files for AI processing; other file types (PPT, DOCX) can be uploaded but are not AI-indexed.</li>
    <li><strong>Real-time Collaboration:</strong> The platform supports sharing but does not implement real-time co-editing or collaborative annotation features.</li>
    <li><strong>Scalability:</strong> The current deployment is optimized for institutional-scale usage (hundreds to thousands of users); hyper-scale deployment would require infrastructure enhancements.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<!-- ===== CHAPTER 2: SYSTEM ANALYSIS ===== -->
<div class="page-break">
  <h1>CHAPTER 2<br/>SYSTEM ANALYSIS</h1>

  <h2>2.1 Literature Survey</h2>
  <p>A thorough review of existing academic resource management systems, e-learning platforms, and AI-augmented educational tools was conducted to identify gaps and inform the design of Study Share.</p>

  <h3>2.1.1 Existing E-Learning Management Systems</h3>
  <p><strong>Moodle (2002):</strong> Moodle is the world's most widely deployed open-source LMS. While feature-rich with quiz engines, forums, and grading tools, Moodle is designed primarily for structured course delivery by faculty. Students cannot freely contribute materials, and the interface is complex for casual use. There is no built-in AI-powered document interaction. Moodle requires institutional deployment and administration, making it impractical for self-organized student communities [1].</p>
  <br/>
  <p><strong>Google Classroom (2014):</strong> Google Classroom provides a lightweight alternative to Moodle, deeply integrated with Google Drive and Google Docs. However, it is tightly controlled by instructors: only teachers can create classes and distribute materials. Students have no mechanism to contribute peer resources, and materials cannot be browsed by academic parameters like semester or branch. Search is limited to title-based lookup [2].</p>
  <br/>
  <p><strong>NPTEL / Swayam (2014):</strong> India's national e-learning initiative provides high-quality video lectures and course materials from IITs and IIMs. However, NPTEL is designed for standardized national courses and does not accommodate institution-specific materials such as university examination question papers, branch-specific notes, or teacher-uploaded supplements [3].</p>
  <br/>
  <p><strong>Academia.edu / ResearchGate:</strong> These platforms facilitate research paper sharing among academics and researchers. They are not designed for undergraduate study materials, lack local institutional categorization, and do not support AI-powered Q&amp;A on uploaded content [4].</p>
  <br/>
  <p><strong>Notion / Confluence:</strong> Wiki-style knowledge bases used by some student communities for collaborative note-taking. While flexible, they lack structured academic categorization, role-based access control, PDF processing pipelines, and AI document interaction [5].</p>

  <h3>2.1.2 AI in Education</h3>
  <p><strong>Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) [6]:</strong> Lewis et al. (2020) introduced RAG, combining dense retrieval from vector databases with generative language models to produce factually grounded answers. Study Share implements a RAG-inspired architecture where PDF content is vectorized using embeddings, stored in Pinecone, and used to augment Gemini API prompts for document Q&amp;A.</p>
  <br/>
  <p><strong>ChatPDF and Humata.ai:</strong> Commercial tools that implement PDF Q&amp;A using LLMs. Study Share differentiates itself by integrating document Q&amp;A within a structured academic repository, providing context (subject, semester, year) alongside the AI interaction, and maintaining a shared institutional knowledge base rather than per-user isolated uploads [7].</p>
  <br/>
  <p><strong>Vector Databases in Information Retrieval [8]:</strong> Johnson et al. (2019) demonstrated the effectiveness of approximate nearest neighbor (ANN) search for dense embeddings in large-scale retrieval tasks (FAISS). Pinecone extends this concept as a managed cloud vector database, enabling Study Share to implement semantic similarity search without infrastructure overhead.</p>

