<!-- ===== APPENDICES ===== -->
<div class="page-break">
  <h1>APPENDIX A – USER MANUAL</h1>

  <h2>A.1 Getting Started</h2>
  <h3>A.1.1 System Requirements (End User)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Modern web browser: Google Chrome 90+, Mozilla Firefox 88+, Apple Safari 14+, Microsoft Edge 90+</li>
    <li>Active internet connection (minimum 2 Mbps recommended for PDF viewing)</li>
    <li>A valid Google account for authentication</li>
    <li>JavaScript must be enabled in the browser</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>A.1.2 First-Time Registration</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Navigate to the Study Share platform URL in your browser.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>"Get Started"</strong> on the landing page.</li>
    <li>On the authentication page, click <strong>"Sign in with Google"</strong>.</li>
    <li>Select your Google account from the popup. Allow necessary permissions.</li>
    <li>You will be redirected to the <strong>Profile Completion</strong> page.</li>
    <li>Select your role: <strong>Student</strong> or <strong>Teacher</strong>.</li>
    <li>Fill in your profile details:
      <ul>
        <li><em>Students:</em> Full Name, Branch, Semester, College, Enrollment Number</li>
        <li><em>Teachers:</em> Full Name (requires admin verification before full access)</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Click <strong>"Complete Profile"</strong>. You will be redirected to the Dashboard.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>A.1.3 Browsing Materials</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>From the Dashboard, materials are listed with filter options at the top.</li>
    <li>Use the <strong>Branch</strong>, <strong>Semester</strong>, <strong>Year</strong>, and <strong>Subject</strong> dropdowns to filter materials.</li>
    <li>Use the <strong>Search bar</strong> to find materials by keyword.</li>
    <li>Click on any material card to open the <strong>Material Viewer</strong>.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>A.1.4 Using AI Document Chat</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Open any material that shows status <strong>"Ready"</strong> (not "Processing").</li>
    <li>The PDF viewer opens with an <strong>AI Chat panel</strong> on the right (or as a tab on mobile).</li>
    <li>Type your question in the input box at the bottom of the chat panel.</li>
    <li>Press Enter or click the Send button.</li>
    <li>The AI will respond with an answer based on the document's content.</li>
    <li><em>Note: AI responses are generated from document content and may not always be 100% accurate. Always verify critical information.</em></li>
  </ol>

  <h3>A.1.5 Uploading Materials</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Click the <strong>"+"</strong> button (Upload) in the navigation bar or bottom nav on mobile.</li>
    <li>Fill in the material details: Title, Subject, Subject Code, Branch, Semester, Year, Description (optional).</li>
    <li>Click <strong>"Choose File"</strong> and select a PDF file (max 10 MB).</li>
    <li>Click <strong>"Upload Material"</strong>.</li>
    <li>The material will appear in "My Uploads" with status <strong>"Processing"</strong>.</li>
    <li>Processing typically completes within 1–5 minutes depending on file size.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>A.1.6 Using the Code Editor</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Navigate to <strong>"Editor"</strong> from the bottom navigation (mobile) or sidebar (desktop).</li>
    <li>Select your programming language from the language dropdown in the OneCompiler toolbar.</li>
    <li>Write or paste your code in the editor panel.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>"RUN"</strong> to execute the code.</li>
    <li>View output in the I/O panel.</li>
    <li>Optionally load sample programs from the <strong>"Samples"</strong> menu for practice.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>A.2 Admin Guide</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Navigate to <strong>/admin/login</strong> and enter admin credentials.</li>
    <li>From the Admin Dashboard, view platform statistics (users, materials, downloads).</li>
    <li>Under <strong>"Users"</strong>: search, view profiles, or delete users.</li>
    <li>Under <strong>"Teachers"</strong>: review pending teacher applications and click <strong>"Verify"</strong> to approve.</li>
    <li>Under <strong>"Materials"</strong>: view all uploaded content; delete inappropriate materials.</li>
  </ol>
</div>

<div class="page-break">
  <h1>APPENDIX B – INSTALLATION GUIDE</h1>

  <h2>B.1 Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Node.js v18.0.0 or higher (<a href="https://nodejs.org">https://nodejs.org</a>)</li>
    <li>npm v9.0+ (bundled with Node.js)</li>
    <li>MongoDB (local instance or MongoDB Atlas cluster)</li>
    <li>Redis (local instance v7+)</li>
    <li>Git v2.40+</li>
    <li>Firebase project with Authentication and Firestore enabled</li>
    <li>Cloudinary account</li>
    <li>Google Gemini API key</li>
    <li>Pinecone account and API key</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>B.2 Backend Setup</h2>
  <div class="code"># 1. Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/satendra03/Study-Share.git
cd Study-Share/backend

# 2. Install dependencies
npm install

# 3. Create environment file
cp .env.example .env
# Edit .env with your credentials:
# MONGODB_URI, FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID, FIREBASE_PRIVATE_KEY,
# CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME, CLOUDINARY_API_KEY,
# CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET, GEMINI_API_KEY,
# PINECONE_API_KEY, NVIDIA_OCR_API_KEY, REDIS_HOST, REDIS_PORT

# 4. Start the backend server
npm run dev

# Server starts at http://localhost:5000</div>

  <h2>B.3 Frontend Setup</h2>
  <div class="code"># In a new terminal
cd Study-Share/frontend

# 1. Install dependencies
npm install

# 2. Create environment file
cp .env.local.example .env.local
# Edit .env.local:
# NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://localhost:5000/api
# NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY=...
# NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=...
# NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=...
# NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID=...

# 3. Start the frontend
npm run dev

# Frontend starts at http://localhost:3000</div>

